'''Anthony J. Bryant''' (February 14, 1961 – December 25, 2013) was an American author and editor.
==Biography== Anthony J. Bryant was born Feb. 14, 1961 in [[Franklin, Indiana]], and was adopted at age 5 by Robert M. and Margaret Bryant.<ref name="obit">"[http://dailyjournal.net/view/obit/16748/#.Ur5Tz5Dnb0x Obituary: Anthony J. ‘Tony’ Bryant, Franklin]," ''Daily Journal'', Franklin, Indiana, Dec 28, 2013.</ref>
After Bob Bryant's death in 1967, Tony and his mother moved to Miami Shores, Fla., where he spent his youth and attended Pinecrest Preparatory School.<ref name="obit"/> After graduating from [[Florida State University]] in 1983 with a [[bachelor's degree]] in [[Japanese studies]], he completed his graduate studies in Japanese studies (history, [[Japanese language|language]], and [[armor]]) at Takoshoku University in Tokyo, graduating in 1986. Bryant resided in Japan from 1986 to 1992.<ref name="obit"/> He also earned an [[Master of Arts|M.A.]] in Japanese from [[Indiana University Bloomington]] in 2003.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books/about/Iwaya_No_S%C5%8Dshi.html?id=5z0eAQAAMAAJ Iwaya No Sōshi: A Translation and Commentary]</ref>
An authority on the making of Japanese armor, he joined the ''Nihon Katchū Bugu Kenkyū Hozon Kai'' ("Japan Association for Arms and Armor Preservation"), and was one of four non-[[Asian people|Asian]] members. While living in Japan, he also worked as a features editor for the ''[[Mainichi Daily News]]'', and as editor for the ''[[Tokyo Journal]]'', an English language monthly magazine.<ref name="obit"/>
Bryant was the author of four books for Osprey Military Publishing on [[samurai]] history, and co-authored, with [[Mark Arsenault]], the core rulebook for the feudal Japanese role-playing game ''[[Sengoku (role-playing game)|Sengoku]]''.<ref name="obit"/> He was a [[History of Japan|historian of Japan]] specializing in [[Kamakura Period|Kamakura]], [[Muromachi Period|Muromachi]], and [[Momoyama period]] warrior culture.{{citation needed|date=January 2014}} His areas of interest also included [[Heian Period|Heian-period]] court structure and society and [[Japanese literature]].{{citation needed|date=January 2014}}
After returning from Japan, in 1995 he became the editor of ''[[Dragon (magazine)|Dragon Magazine]]'', the flagship publication of [[TSR, Inc.]], the creators of the role-playing game ''[[Dungeons & Dragons]]''.<ref name="obit"/> He was the editor for only 8 issues of ''Dragon'', before [[Dave Gross]] took over.
Bryant died on December 25, 2013, at St. Francis Health in Indianapolis.<ref name="obit"/>
